"""
MKT Context Commentary — Judges chapters 7–8
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-judges-7-8.py

Ch7: Gideon's 300 — reduction of forces, night attack, Midianite rout (25 verses)
Ch8: Aftermath — Ephraim's grievance, Succoth and Penuel, Zebah and Zalmunna,
     kingship offer rejected, ephod, Gideon's death and Israel's relapse (35 verses)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>Gideon's camp at <strong>Ein Harod</strong> (Spring of Harod, from <em>ḥāraḏ</em> = to tremble) sits at the foot of Mount Gilboa at the eastern edge of the Jezreel Valley. The spring still flows today and is identified with modern ʿAin Jalud near Kibbutz Gidona. The Jezreel Valley (also called the Plain of Esdraelon) is one of the most strategically important corridors in the ancient Levant — it is the natural route connecting the Mediterranean coast to the Jordan Valley and Transjordan. The Midianite-Amalekite forces have encamped at <strong>Moreh Hill</strong> (<em>gibʿat hammôreh</em>), identified with Jebel Dahy (Little Hermon) north of the valley — the two camps face each other across approximately 6 kilometers of flat valley floor. Control of the Jezreel Valley controlled Israel's agricultural heartland and north-south trade routes.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The reduction of Gideon's force from 32,000 to 300 is intelligible against the background of <strong>Deuteronomic holy war law</strong> (Deut 20:1-9). The principle of 'too many' (<em>rāb</em>) for YHWH to work through reflects the theology of <em>ḥērem</em> warfare: when Israel's victory can be credited to YHWH's power rather than military superiority, the surrounding nations cannot claim it was merely a human military triumph. The fear of Israel 'boasting' (<em>yitpāʾēr</em>) recalls the exact critique YHWH will make of Assyria in Isa 10:15: 'Shall the axe boast over him who hews with it?' The deliberate military weakness that enables supernatural deliverance is a recurring ANE motif in divine warrior traditions, but Israel's version is theologically distinctive: YHWH does not merely assist, he is the primary combatant.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The first reduction test applies <strong>Deut 20:8</strong>: the mustering officer was to ask 'Is there any man who is afraid and fainthearted? Let him go home.' The 22,000 who return home (<em>ṣāpôn</em> — 'toward Gilead' in MT, possibly 'toward Zaphon') represent 68% of the force. Fear was a legitimate disqualification under holy war law because it was contagious — one frightened man could demoralize an entire unit (Deut 20:8: 'lest he make his brothers' heart melt as his own'). That the majority leave is itself a theological statement: YHWH's deliverances are designed to be impossible by human calculation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The second reduction moves to the <strong>Harod Spring</strong> itself — the water test is conducted at the source of the army's water supply, a militarily practical location. YHWH instructs Gideon that the test will further separate the 10,000 into two groups. The purpose of the test is divine selection, not human merit: neither group is morally or militarily superior. The theological point is YHWH's prerogative to select his instruments by criteria that appear arbitrary to human observers, demonstrating that the victory cannot be credited to the quality of the soldiers chosen.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The water test at Harod: <strong>those who lap water like a dog</strong> (300 men) are separated from those who kneel down to drink (9,700). The practical distinction is posture: kneeling to drink requires bending low with both hands to the water, while lapping from the cupped hand keeps the head up and eyes forward. Military historians have noted that the lapping posture is more alert (able to observe the surroundings) than the kneeling posture. Whether the selection is based on alertness, humility, or is entirely arbitrary in human terms, the text is clear that YHWH makes the selection — the criterion reveals divine prerogative, not human desert.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The final count: <strong>300 men</strong> who lap versus 9,700 who kneel. The number 300 is significant in ANE military tradition as a functional unit size — the Spartan 300 at Thermopylae (480 BCE) are the most famous example, but the Ugaritic texts mention elite corps of similar size. However, 300 against a Midianite force described in v12 as 'like locusts' — camels 'without number' — is strategically insane by any human reckoning. The gap between 300 and hundreds of thousands is the theological gap that YHWH fills: the victory is demonstrably his because the numbers make human victory impossible.</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH's promise: <strong>'With the 300 men who lapped I will save you'</strong> — the divine declaration precedes the battle by a night. In ANE military culture, receiving a divine oracle before battle was essential for morale and was often sought through divination (Midianite dream interpretation in v13 is a parallel practice). Here YHWH gives the oracle unsolicited and direct: no priestly intermediary, no sacrificial ritual required. The rest of the 9,700 are dismissed with their provisions: they are not judged or disgraced, merely released. The logistics of this release — feeding and equipping 9,700 men — suggest Gideon had substantial base camp support.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The 300 take the <strong>provisions and trumpets</strong> from the dismissed 9,700. The trumpet (<em>šôpār</em>) here is not a musical instrument but a military signaling device — a ram's horn or hollowed-out horn used to coordinate unit movements and signals across a battlefield. The Midianite camp is below in the valley: the terrain gives Gideon's hillside position a tactical advantage (sound carries well downhill) and a psychological one (attacking from the high ground). Gideon's night reconnaissance (v9-15) shows careful military planning even within the supernatural framework of the campaign.</p>",
    "9": "<p>YHWH instructs Gideon to <strong>go down against the camp at night</strong>, adding an unusual pastoral option: 'if you are afraid, go down with Purah your servant.' The divine offer of a companion is a recognition of human fear — even the divinely commissioned leader needs encouragement. <strong>Purah</strong> (H6513, possibly 'branch/foliage') serves as Gideon's personal armor-bearer, a standard ANE military role (cf. Saul's armor-bearer, 1 Sam 31:4-6; Jonathan's armor-bearer, 1 Sam 14:1-15). Night raids against enemy camps were a recognized ANE military tactic, particularly effective when the enemy was large, dispersed, and relying on numbers rather than discipline.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The instruction to go down and <strong>listen</strong> to the enemy camp is an intelligence-gathering operation before the attack — standard military reconnaissance. YHWH promises that hearing the enemy will 'strengthen your hands' (<em>ḥizzəqû yāḏeykā</em>), a common ANE expression for gaining courage to act (cf. the same phrase in Neh 6:9; Ezra 1:6). The intelligence mission is not merely practical; it is divinely arranged: YHWH has already prepared the Midianite dream (v13-14) that Gideon will overhear. The reconnaissance and the supernatural encouragement are integrated — YHWH works through both means simultaneously.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Gideon and Purah go to the <strong>edge of the armed men in the camp</strong> — the outer perimeter of the Midianite force. The Midianite encampment would have been a sprawling tent-city: the camels alone numbered in the tens of thousands (v12). Pastoral nomadic armies like the Midianites did not form tight defensive perimeters; they camped with their livestock in a dispersed pattern that gave them early warning through animal noise rather than human sentinels. This open perimeter enabled Gideon to approach close enough to overhear conversation inside a tent.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The narrator describes the Midianite force: <strong>'like locusts for multitude'</strong> and their camels <strong>'without number, as the sand of the sea'</strong>. The locust comparison (<em>ʾarbeh</em> H697) is a standard ANE hyperbole for overwhelming military forces (cf. Jer 46:23; Nah 3:15). The camel detail is historically significant: the widespread domestication of camels for military use (as opposed to pack transport) is archaeologically attested from the 12th century BCE onward — the Midianite use of camels here is one of the earliest attested military applications, giving their raids the speed and range impossible with donkey transport. The Jezreel Valley is approximately 40 km from Midianite territory across the Jordan: camel mobility made the annual raids logistically feasible.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Gideon arrives to hear a Midianite soldier recounting a <strong>dream to his companion</strong>. Dream interpretation was a major feature of ANE divination and military culture: the Assyrian king's dreams were recorded and professionally interpreted; the Ugaritic texts contain dream reports before battle. The Midianite's dream of a <strong>barley loaf rolling into the camp</strong> and overturning the tent is a dream of reversal — the attacker becomes the victim. That the Midianite soldier spontaneously interprets this dream as Israel's God giving them into Gideon's hand (v14) demonstrates that YHWH's reputation had preceded him: Israel's enemies knew who YHWH was even if Israel was forgetting.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Midianite soldier's interpretation identifies the rolling loaf as <strong>'nothing other than the sword of Gideon son of Joash, a man of Israel'</strong>. The <strong>barley loaf</strong> (<em>ṣəlîl leḥem śəʿōrîm</em>) carries social weight: barley was the poor man's grain, wheat being superior. A barley loaf overturning a warrior's tent is an image of low-status power defeating high-status military might — precisely the message of the entire Gideon narrative. The interpretation comes from within the enemy camp, unprompted by any Israelite. YHWH ensures that Gideon hears exactly the encouragement needed at exactly the moment he needs it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Gideon's response to the dream interpretation: he <strong>worships</strong> (<em>wayyištaḥû</em>) — prostrating himself in acknowledgment of YHWH's action. This is the only recorded act of worship Gideon performs at the moment of divine encouragement, and it precedes the battle rather than following it. His command to rise immediately — <strong>'Arise, for YHWH has given the host of Midian into your hand'</strong> — uses the perfect tense to describe a future event as already accomplished (the 'prophetic perfect'): from YHWH's perspective the battle is over before it begins. The return to the Israelite camp and immediate organization for attack shows that the divine promise generates decisive action, not passive waiting.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The battle strategy: <strong>three companies of 100</strong>, each man equipped with a <strong>trumpet</strong> (<em>šôpār</em>), an <strong>empty clay jar</strong> (<em>kad rêqām</em> H3537), and a <strong>torch</strong> (<em>lappîḏ</em> H3940) inside the jar. The clay jar functioned as a baffle to conceal the torchlight during approach: the torch produced light visible from a distance that would alert sentinels. By covering the torch with a sealed clay jar, 300 men could move through the darkness undetected. The strategic concept is a night psychological attack using simultaneous surprise on multiple points of the perimeter — three flanks, each creating maximum noise and light at the same moment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Gideon places himself at the <strong>head of the middle company</strong> — leading from the front was the ANE expectation of military commanders. The instruction 'watch me and do likewise' establishes Gideon as the signal source: the other companies time their action to his lead. The night timing chosen — the <strong>beginning of the middle watch</strong> (v19) — is militarily calculated: the Israelite night was divided into three watches (evening, midnight, morning), and the change from the first to the middle watch (around midnight) was when sentinels were changing and attention was lowest.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The battle cry: <strong>'For YHWH and for Gideon'</strong> (<em>laYHWH ûlᵊGidʿôn</em>). In ANE military culture, battle cries were the oral equivalent of military standards — they identified which army you were with and galvanized troops in the confusion of battle. The pairing of YHWH's name with Gideon's is unusual: in Israel's holy war tradition, YHWH alone is the warrior (Exod 15:3: 'YHWH is a man of war'). The inclusion of Gideon's name alongside YHWH's will later be read by some as the beginning of Gideon's monarchical ambitions, though the narrative here presents it without censure.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The attack is executed <strong>'at the beginning of the middle watch, when they had just set the watch'</strong> — the period just after the guards changed at midnight, when the new watch was at its most alert but the camp was most disoriented by the transition. The <strong>smashing of the clay jars</strong> (<em>wayyišbərû hakkaḏîm</em>) simultaneously on all three sides produced a sustained crashing noise that could sound like the approach of a large force. In a dark encampment of hundreds of thousands, the simultaneous explosion of sound and light on all sides would be catastrophically disorienting.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The 300 hold <strong>torches in their left hands and trumpets in their right</strong> — an asymmetric display. The torch-and-trumpet combination serves psychological rather than conventional military purposes: they are not holding weapons. The three-company cry — <strong>'A sword for YHWH and for Gideon!'</strong> — is shouted simultaneously around the entire perimeter. Archaeological experiments with ram's-horn trumpets show they carry approximately 500 meters in open terrain; 300 trumpets on three sides of a camp would create a wall of sound suggesting thousands of attackers. The torch-light would create moving, disorienting impressions of numbers in the darkness.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Each of the 300 stands in his place — <strong>no conventional attack follows</strong>. The Israelites do not charge or engage in hand-to-hand combat; they maintain their perimeter positions and let the panic do the work. This is the key to the strategy: they create conditions for the Midianite army to destroy itself. <strong>'All the army fled'</strong> (<em>wayyānās kol-hammaḥaneh</em>) — a mass rout of an enormous force, not a military defeat in the conventional sense but a stampede triggered by supernatural terror.</p>",
    "22": "<p>YHWH sets <strong>'the sword of each man against his companion'</strong> (<em>wayyāśem YHWH ʾēt ḥereb ʾîš bərēʿēhû</em>). This idiom describes the confusion of friendly fire in a panicked camp at night: soldiers cannot distinguish allies from enemies. The phenomenon of a panicked army attacking itself is documented in ANE and classical sources (Herodotus records a similar event at Marathon where Persian cavalry trampled Persian infantry). The Midianite rout carries the army south and east: to <strong>Beth-shittah toward Zererah, as far as the bank of Abel-meholah</strong> (v22), identifying three points of the flight path across the Jordan Valley.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Israelite men from <strong>Naphtali, Asher, and all Manasseh</strong> join the pursuit of the Midianites — the emergency call-up that had been dismissed in vv2-3 can now participate safely in mopping up. The pursuit extends south and east across the Jezreel Valley toward the Jordan River. The geography of the flight path is archaeologically consistent with the Midianites' likely route back to Transjordan: down the Harod valley through Beth-shean to the Jordan fords. Gideon's capture of the Jordan fords (v24) is the strategic move that prevents the majority of the army from escaping.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Gideon sends messengers to the <strong>hill country of Ephraim</strong> — the high ground west of the Jordan and north of Jerusalem — with orders to seize the Jordan fords. The Ephraimites respond and capture the fords <strong>'as far as Beth-barah'</strong>, cutting off the Midianite army's escape route. <strong>Oreb</strong> (<em>ʿōrēb</em> H6157, 'raven') and <strong>Zeeb</strong> (<em>zəʾēb</em> H2062, 'wolf') are two Midianite commanders; their names are animal totems, which was common in ANE military culture for officers. Their execution at specific geographical sites — the rock of Oreb and the winepress of Zeeb — creates place-names that commemorated the victory for later generations.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The heads of Oreb and Zeeb are brought to Gideon <strong>'beyond the Jordan'</strong> (<em>mēʿēḇer layyardēn</em>), indicating that Gideon has already crossed the Jordan in pursuit of the main force (ch8 continues the pursuit into Transjordan). The presentation of enemy commanders' heads was standard practice in ANE warfare for reporting a victory and confirming the kill (cf. Goliath's head, 1 Sam 17:57; the heads sent to Jehu, 2 Kgs 10:7-8). The site names — <strong>Rock of Oreb</strong> (<em>ṣûr ʿōrēb</em>) and <strong>Winepress of Zeeb</strong> (<em>yaqeb zəʾēb</em>) — are preserved in prophetic memory: Isaiah 10:26 and Psalm 83:11 invoke these victories as paradigm examples of YHWH's defeat of Israel's enemies.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>Ephraim's angry confrontation with Gideon reflects the <strong>tribal politics of pre-monarchic Israel</strong>. Ephraim was one of the dominant tribes of the central hill country, claiming descent from Joseph's younger son (Gen 48:17-19) with the birthright blessing. Ephraim's anger (<em>wayyərîḇûn ʾittô bəḥozqāh</em>, they contended with him vigorously) over not being called to the initial battle is the same grievance they will later bring against Jephthah (12:1-6) — Jephthah's less diplomatic response to the same complaint triggers civil war. Gideon's diplomatic reply (vv2-3) successfully defuses the situation, demonstrating the political skills required of an effective judge alongside the military ones.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Gideon's diplomatic response uses a <strong>proverbial comparison</strong> (<em>māšāl</em>): the gleaning of Ephraim's grapes is better than the vintage of Abiezer. <strong>Gleaning</strong> (<em>ʿôlēlôt</em> H5955) was the harvest activity of the poor (Lev 19:9-10; Ruth 2) — the scattered grapes left after the main harvest. Gideon demotes his own clan's ('Abiezer') accomplishment to a 'vintage' and elevates Ephraim's lesser participation (capturing two commanders) to 'gleaning' — a reversal that satisfies Ephraim's pride by making their contribution sound greater. The capture of Oreb and Zeeb (v1) was indeed strategically significant: cutting off the commanders prevented an organized retreat and regrouping.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Gideon's declaration — <strong>'What have I done in comparison with you?'</strong> — is the completion of the proverbial comparison. The Ephraimites' anger subsided (<em>wayyirep rûḥām mēʿālāyw</em>, 'their spirit/anger relaxed from upon him') when they heard the flattering framing. This is one of the few conflict-resolution moments in Judges that succeeds: Gideon uses wisdom to prevent intra-tribal violence that would undermine the victory. The contrast with Jephthah (12:1-6) who gives a factual answer and triggers civil war is instructive: in Israel's tribal structure, managing honor was as important as military competence.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The pursuit continues <strong>across the Jordan</strong> into Transjordan — Gideon with the 300 men, now described as <strong>exhausted yet pursuing</strong> (<em>ʿăyēpîm wərōdepîm</em>). The phrase captures the combination of physical depletion and relentless determination. Transjordan (the territory east of the Jordan River) was the home territory of Midian: Gideon is taking the fight into enemy homeland rather than simply repelling a raid. The cities of Succoth and Penuel that Gideon approaches (vv5-9) were Israelite (or at least trans-Jordanian Israelite) towns, making their refusal to assist all the more politically significant.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>Succoth</strong> (<em>sukkôt</em> H5523, 'booths/shelters') was a town in the Jordan Valley in the territory of Gad (Josh 13:27). Its precise location is debated: candidates include Tell Deir ʿAllā and Tell el-Ekhsas. Gideon asks for <strong>bread</strong> for his troops — a supply request, not a donation request, which makes the refusal more pointed. The leaders of Succoth refuse on pragmatic political grounds: <strong>'Are the hands of Zebah and Zalmunna already in your hand?'</strong> — they are not convinced Gideon will win, and they are more afraid of Midianite reprisals than they trust in YHWH's promise. This is rational political calculation in the absence of covenant faith.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Succoth's refusal (<em>hăḵap Zeḇaḥ wəṣalmunnāʿ kāp bəyāḏekā</em> — 'is the palm of Zebah and Zalmunna already in your hand?') uses the idiom of <strong>the 'palm' of the king as symbol of authority and capture</strong> — seizing the king's hand/palm meant actual capture of the person. Succoth's sarcastic conditional refusal ('when you actually have them, then we'll feed your men') shows they regard Gideon's mission as unlikely to succeed. The punishment Gideon promises — <strong>threshing with desert thorns and briers</strong> (<em>dôš</em> + <em>qôṣ hammidbar wəhabbārqānîm</em>) — is an agricultural metaphor for a painful corporal punishment: dragging thorn-branches over human bodies as if they were grain being threshed.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>Desert thorns and briers</strong> (<em>qôṣ hammidbar wəhabbārqānîm</em>) — <em>qôṣ</em> (H6975) refers to thorny plants common in the Transjordanian wilderness (brambles, possibly <em>Ziziphus spina-christi</em> or similar); <em>bārqānîm</em> (H1303, briers — rare word, possibly the thorn-bush <em>Rubus sanctus</em>). Threshing (<em>dûš</em> H1758) was done by dragging a heavy wooden sledge fitted with flint or metal teeth across grain on a threshing floor. Applied to human bodies, this would be a form of laceration torture. That Gideon promises this to Israelite town leaders for non-cooperation reveals the level of coercive authority the judges exercised over reluctant communities.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>Penuel</strong> (<em>pənûʾēl</em> H6439, 'face of God') was the site where Jacob wrestled with the divine messenger (Gen 32:30-31) — a sacred place in Israelite memory. Its identification is uncertain; Tell edh-Dhahab esh-Sherqiyeh on the Jabbok River is a candidate. Penuel's refusal mirrors Succoth's: they also decline to provision Gideon's force. The fact that a place bearing the name 'face of God' and associated with the patriarch Jacob's divine encounter refuses to support YHWH's deliverer is an irony the text does not comment on explicitly but that a Hebrew reader would feel keenly.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Gideon's threat to Penuel: <strong>'When I come back in peace I will tear down this tower'</strong> (<em>bəšûḇî bəšālôm ʾetrōs ʾet-hammiggāḏāl hazzeh</em>). The <strong>tower</strong> (<em>miggāḏāl</em> H4026) was likely a civic fortification tower — the dominant architectural defensive feature of Transjordanian towns in this period. Destroying a tower was a standard punishment for a rebellious town in ANE practice (cf. Abimelech's destruction of Shechem's tower, 9:46-49). Gideon's two punishment threats (Succoth: threshing with thorns; Penuel: tower destruction) correspond to the two types of assets each town prioritizes — civic prestige for Penuel, agricultural production for Succoth.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>Zebah and Zalmunna</strong> (<em>zeḇaḥ</em> H2078, 'sacrifice'; <em>ṣalmunnāʿ</em> H6759, possibly 'shade/protection denied') were at <strong>Karkor</strong> with approximately <strong>15,000 men</strong> — the remnant of the eastern Midianite force after the collapse at Jezreel. Karkor (<em>qarqōr</em> H7174) is likely in Wadi Sirhan, deep in the Transjordanian desert southeast of the Dead Sea — approximately 150-200 km from the Jezreel Valley. The distance of the pursuit demonstrates the scope of Gideon's campaign: this is not a border defense action but an offensive campaign that carries Israel's army deep into Midianite territory.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Gideon approaches via the <strong>caravan route east of Nobah and Jogbehah</strong> — the desert caravan road (<em>derek haʾōhălîm</em>, 'road of the tent-dwellers') that ran through Transjordan, distinct from the main agricultural road. This route gave Gideon a surprise approach: the Midianite remnant felt secure at Karkor because pursuit via the main roads had apparently ceased. The caravan route through nomadic territory was the road least expected for a military force — Gideon's strategic creativity extends to the approach as well as the attack. <strong>'Struck the army when they felt secure'</strong> — the Hebrew <em>ḇeṭaḥ</em> (H983) means confidence that proves unfounded, a state of false security.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The capture of Zebah and Zalmunna is the strategic goal of the entire extended campaign: <strong>'all the army fled, and he captured the two kings'</strong>. The flight of the army at Karkor mirrors the earlier rout at Jezreel: the same pattern of supernatural panic followed by complete route. The two kings are captured alive rather than killed immediately — Gideon reserves their execution as a judicial act (vv18-21) rather than a battlefield kill. The capture of enemy kings was the highest possible military-political achievement in ANE warfare: it demonstrated absolute dominance and enabled the conqueror to exact maximum symbolic humiliation through the manner of execution.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Gideon returns from battle <strong>'by the ascent of Heres'</strong> (<em>mimmáʿăleh heḥeres</em>) — likely a pass on the return route from Transjordan into the Jordan Valley, possibly the same as the Ascent of Adummim. The young man he captures at Succoth (<em>naʿar</em> H5288 — a young male, possibly a scribe or administrative assistant) is asked to write down the names of Succoth's leaders. The detail that the young man <strong>wrote for him</strong> (<em>wayyiktob ʾēlāyw</em>) is a significant historical note: literacy at a practical administrative level existed in Israelite towns in the pre-monarchic period. The writing of 77 names implies a list of civic leaders with their identities — a reasonably sophisticated administrative function.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The written list of <strong>77 elders and leaders of Succoth</strong> (<em>śarê sukkôt wə-zəqēnêhā šiḇʿîm wəšiḇʿāh ʾîš</em>) is an unusually specific number, suggesting an actual historical record. <strong>Seventy-seven</strong> is a number associated with complete or full judgment (Gen 4:24: Lamech's sevenfold-sevenfold vengeance) — whether the number is literal or symbolic is debated, but its specificity lends credibility. The scene demonstrates that pre-monarchic Israelite towns had identifiable civic leadership structures: <em>śārîm</em> (officials/princes) and <em>zəqēnîm</em> (elders), corresponding to executive and deliberative functions.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Gideon returns to confront Succoth with <strong>Zebah and Zalmunna</strong> in tow — the fulfilment of the condition Succoth had set: 'Are the palms of Zebah and Zalmunna already in your hand?' (v6). The captured kings function as proof of victory and as the instrument of Gideon's accusation: Succoth had doubted YHWH's ability to deliver, and YHWH delivered. The confrontation follows the pattern of covenant lawsuit: the accusation (<em>hinnēh zeḇaḥ wəṣalmunnāʿ</em>, 'here are Zebah and Zalmunna'), the reminder of the earlier refusal, and the announcement of judgment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The punishment of Succoth: Gideon <strong>takes the elders of the city and thorns and briers of the wilderness</strong> and 'teaches' (<em>wayyôdaʿ</em>) the men of Succoth with them. The verb <em>yāḏaʿ</em> (to know/teach — here in the Hiphil causative: to make them know/to teach) is used with dark irony: the punishment is itself the lesson. The same verb will appear in v17 for Penuel ('he taught the men of Penuel,' the tower). In ANE royal inscriptions, punishing rebellious vassals with harsh corporal punishment was framed as 'teaching a lesson' to others who might consider similar disloyalty.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Penuel's punishment: Gideon <strong>tears down the tower</strong> as threatened (v9) and <strong>kills the men of the city</strong>. The escalation from Succoth (punishment of leaders) to Penuel (destruction of defensive infrastructure plus execution) reflects the distinction between corporal punishment and execution: Succoth's leadership was physically punished and presumably survived; Penuel's men were killed. The destruction of the tower (<em>wayyitrōs ʾet-hammiggāḏāl</em>) removed Penuel's primary defensive asset, making the city vulnerable to future raiders — a punishment with lasting strategic consequences beyond the immediate deaths.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Gideon interrogates Zebah and Zalmunna about <strong>the men they killed at Tabor</strong>. <strong>Mount Tabor</strong> (<em>har tāḇôr</em> H8396) rises 575 meters above the Jezreel Valley floor — a prominent landmark and strategic high point. The men killed there are identified in v19 as Gideon's brothers, sons of his mother. The killing of Gideon's brothers at Tabor was not part of the Jezreel Valley battle narrative (chs.6-7) and must be a separate incident — likely an earlier Midianite raid. The kings' description of the dead men — <strong>'each of them resembled the son of a king'</strong> — is either a compliment designed to flatter Gideon or an honest observation about the bearing of the men of Gideon's family.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Gideon's declaration: <strong>'They were my brothers, sons of my mother'</strong> — the emphasis on the maternal bond rather than paternal suggests blood-kin solidarity (<em>bənê ʾimmî</em>, sons of my mother). In the ancient Near East, the maternal bond was sometimes stronger than the paternal in terms of blood solidarity, especially in polygamous households where different wives' sons were half-brothers. <strong>'If you had saved them alive, I would not kill you'</strong> — the conditional is counterfactual: they did not save them, so Gideon is obligated by blood-revenge law (<em>gōʾēl haddām</em>, kinsman redeemer of blood, Num 35:19) to execute them. The execution is framed as judicial rather than vengeful.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Gideon commands <strong>his firstborn son Jether</strong> to strike down the kings. Jether's fear and failure to draw his sword reflects the ANE warrior-culture expectation: killing a captured king was an act of military honor, but only a proven warrior could claim it. A youth who had not yet proven himself in battle would be shamed by executing bound prisoners rather than honored, and the kings know this: their response in v21 — 'Rise yourself and fall upon us, for as the man is, so is his strength' — is a calculated taunt that acknowledges only Gideon as a worthy executioner.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Zebah and Zalmunna's appeal: <strong>'Rise yourself and fall upon us, for as the man is, so is his strength'</strong> (<em>ʿămōd-ʾattāh ûpəgaʿ-bānû kî kaʾîš gəḇûrātô</em>). The proverb <em>kaʾîš gəḇûrātô</em> ('as the man, so his strength') asserts that the execution honors both killer and killed: only a man of full strength can honorably kill a king. They prefer death by Gideon's hand to death by a boy's. The <strong>crescent ornaments</strong> (<em>śahărōnîm</em> H7720) from the camels' necks — lunar crescent decorations in gold or silver — were standard ANE camel decorations attested in Assyrian reliefs and textual sources. Gideon takes them as victory spoils.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The Israelites' offer of hereditary kingship to Gideon — <strong>'Rule over us, you and your son and your grandson'</strong> — represents the political momentum of a successful military campaign translated into a constitutional proposal. The offer is dynastic: not merely lifetime rule but hereditary monarchy (<em>mšl</em>, to rule, the same root as the word for 'proverb': wisdom-rule). The offer comes from 'the men of Israel' rather than tribal elders, suggesting a popular (possibly pan-tribal) movement. The post-battle enthusiasm for military-political monarchy was a recognized ANE pattern: successful generals became kings throughout the ancient world.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Gideon's refusal is the theological pivot of the entire book: <strong>'I will not rule over you, and my son will not rule over you; YHWH will rule over you'</strong> (<em>lōʾ ʾemšōl bākem ʾănî wəlōʾ-yimšōl bənî bākem YHWH yimšōl bākem</em>). The triple structure (I will not / my son will not / YHWH will rule) is a formal theocratic declaration: the <em>mišpāṭ hammelek</em> (right of the king) demanded by Israel in 1 Samuel 8 is precisely what YHWH here claims exclusively. Gideon's answer is the correct theocratic answer — Israel already has a king, YHWH. The refusal will be completely undermined by his actions in vv24-27 and by his naming his son Abimelech ('my father is king,' v31).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Despite refusing the kingship, Gideon asks for the <strong>gold earrings</strong> (<em>nizmê hazzāhāb</em>) from the Ishmaelite spoil. The identification of the enemy as both Midianites (throughout) and Ishmaelites (here and v26) reflects the ethnographic complexity of ANE nomadic confederacies: Midianites and Ishmaelites were related peoples who frequently cooperated economically and militarily (cf. Gen 37:25-28 where both names are used for Joseph's traders). The earring collection from the enemy dead was standard practice after ANE battles. The total weight — <strong>1,700 shekels of gold</strong> (approximately 20 kg) — plus the crescent ornaments, purple garments, and camel chains indicates enormous battlefield wealth.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Israelites spread a garment and each man throws in his earring — a <strong>spontaneous field collection</strong> of voluntary tribute. The scene presupposes a large force: the 300 plus the tribal reinforcements from Naphtali, Asher, and Manasseh (7:23). The garment-spread collection (<em>wayyipresû et-haśśimlāh</em>) is pragmatic field logistics: no box, no bag, a garment laid out is the quickest way to collect many small items from many contributors. That each man contributes willingly (no compulsion is mentioned) reflects the post-victory generosity of a well-rewarded army.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The inventory of Gideon's gold collection: <strong>1,700 shekels of gold</strong> earrings (approximately 20 kg of gold), plus the <strong>crescent ornaments</strong> (<em>śahărōnîm</em>), <strong>pendants</strong> (<em>nəṭipôt</em> H5188, teardrop-shaped jewelry), <strong>purple robes</strong> (<em>bəḡāḏîm hāʾargāmān</em> — royal garments; purple dye from Murex snails was extraordinarily expensive and exclusively associated with royalty in the ANE), and the <strong>camel chains</strong> (<em>hanəzāmîm ʾăšer bəṣawwarê gəmallêhem</em>). The purple robes worn by the Midianite kings and the royal camel decorations signal that Gideon has captured not just a raiding force but the actual royal leadership of Midian. The total spoil would have been equivalent to decades of a single family's income.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Gideon makes an <strong>ephod</strong> (<em>ʾêpôḏ</em> H646) from the gold — the priestly garment used by the high priest at the tabernacle (Exod 28:4-14) and associated with seeking YHWH's will (1 Sam 23:9-12). The problem is its location: <strong>in his city, in Ophrah</strong> — not at Shiloh where the tabernacle was. The ephod becomes a pilgrimage object: <strong>'all Israel whored after it there'</strong> (<em>wayyizni kol-yiśrāʾēl ʾaḥărāyw šam</em>) — the sexual infidelity metaphor for idolatry (cf. the recurring refrain of Israel 'whoring after' other gods). Gideon himself <strong>'snared'</strong> (<em>môqēš</em> H4170) — the same word used for idols as snares (Exod 23:33; Deut 7:16). The man who refused the crown sets up the religious infrastructure of kingship in his own territory.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The victory summary: <strong>Midian was subdued before the people of Israel</strong> and the land had rest <strong>forty years in the days of Gideon</strong>. The forty-year rest is the longest in Judges: Othniel (40 years, 3:11), Deborah (40 years, 5:31), Gideon (40 years, 8:28), and Eli (40 years in the ark period). Forty years is the standard generational unit in biblical chronology (Num 14:33-34: one year for each day of reconnaissance = one generation). The forty-year periods of rest represent a full generation's worth of covenant blessing — peace that outlasts the judge's active career and fills his natural lifetime.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>Jerubbaal son of Joash</strong> (<em>yərubbaʿal ben-yôʾāš</em>) — the name Gideon received when he tore down Baal's altar (6:32): 'let Baal contend against him.' Gideon's formal name in the administrative contexts of ch8 is Jerubbaal rather than Gideon, which may indicate that the two names reflect different source traditions: 'Gideon' (H1439, possibly 'hewer/one who cuts down') is his personal name; 'Jerubbaal' is his honorary/polemical name. <strong>He lived in his house</strong> (<em>wayyēšeḇ yərubbaʿal bəḇêtô</em>) — the retirement of a judge to his house after the period of active deliverance is the standard Judges pattern.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Gideon had <strong>seventy sons from many wives</strong> (<em>šiḇʿîm bānîm yōṣəʾê yərēkô kî nāšîm rabbôt hāyû-lô</em>). The number seventy is the standard ANE royal harem count for a successful king — Ahab had seventy sons (2 Kgs 10:1), and the Ugaritic texts describe royal households with similar numbers. Gideon who refused the kingship lives as a king: many wives, large household, centralized authority in Ophrah. The political infrastructure of monarchy is present even without the title. <strong>Many wives</strong> (<em>nāšîm rabbôt</em>) — polygamy in this period was a sign of wealth and status, the biological expression of political power.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Gideon also had a <strong>concubine in Shechem</strong> (<em>pilegšô ʾăšer biškem</em>) who bore him a son named <strong>Abimelech</strong> (<em>ʾăḇîmeleḵ</em> H40, 'my father is king'). The name is the supreme irony of Gideon's story: the man who declared 'YHWH will rule over you' (v23) names his son 'my father is king.' Whether Gideon gave the name or the Shechemite mother gave it (naming was typically the mother's prerogative in the OT), the name claims royal paternity. Shechem (<em>šekem</em> H7927) was the central sanctuary city of Canaan, associated with Baal-berith (Baal of the Covenant, 9:4) — the concubine's Shechemite origin places Abimelech within Canaanite political networks from birth.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Gideon's death and burial: <strong>he died in good old age</strong> (<em>wayyāmot bəśêḇāh ṭôḇāh</em>) and was buried in the tomb of his father Joash at <strong>Ophrah of the Abiezrites</strong>. The 'good old age' formula is used of Abraham (Gen 25:8) and David (1 Chr 29:28) — it implies honor, completeness, and covenant blessing. Ophrah of the Abiezrites is identified with modern et-Taiyibeh (or alternatively with Afula), in the territory of Manasseh west of the Jordan Valley. The burial in the ancestral tomb maintains the generational continuity that Gideon's multiple sons will violently disrupt in ch9.</p>",
    "33": "<p>After Gideon's death: <strong>'Israel turned again and whored after the Baals'</strong> (<em>wayyāšûḇû bənê-yiśrāʾēl wayyizənû ʾaḥărê haббəʿālîm</em>). The sexual metaphor for idolatry — <em>zānāh</em> (H2181, to commit fornication/whoredom) — is the Deuteronomistic formula for covenant violation (Exod 34:15-16; Deut 31:16; Num 25:1). <strong>Baal-berith</strong> (<em>baʿal bərît</em> H1170, 'lord of the covenant') was Shechem's local deity — a Canaanite god whose name and attribute ('covenant') was a direct parody of YHWH's covenant. Worshiping a Baal called 'Lord of the Covenant' was the theological nadir of syncretism: taking YHWH's defining attribute and attaching it to a Canaanite deity.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Israel <strong>'did not remember YHWH their God who had rescued them from the hand of all their enemies around them'</strong> (<em>wəlōʾ zākərû bənê yiśrāʾēl ʾet-YHWH ʾĕlōhêhem hammaṣṣîl ʾôtām miyyaḏ kol-ʾōyəḇêhem missāḇîḇ</em>). The verb <em>zākar</em> (H2142, to remember) is the covenant memory-term: Israel is called throughout the Torah to 'remember' (Deut 8:2,18; 16:3,12; 24:18,22). Forgetting YHWH's deliverances is the precise failure that the Passover, the Sabbath, and the annual festivals were designed to prevent — the liturgical practices of memory. Their failure is not intellectual amnesia but covenantal ingratitude: they enjoyed the peace Gideon's victories secured and then abandoned the God who gave it.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The final verse: Israel did not show <strong>ḥesed</strong> (<em>ḥāseḏ</em> H2617) to the house of Jerubbaal/Gideon according to all the good he had done for Israel. <em>ḥesed</em> is the covenant loyalty-and-kindness word: the reciprocal faithfulness owed within a covenant relationship. Not showing <em>ḥesed</em> to Gideon's household (which Abimelech will exploit in ch9 by massacring his seventy brothers) is a failure at two levels: horizontal (human covenant loyalty to a benefactor) and vertical (v34: forgetting YHWH). The two failures are inseparable in Deuteronomistic theology — covenant with YHWH and covenant faithfulness to fellow covenant members are indivisible. The book of Ruth, set in this same period, will explore what true <em>ḥesed</em> looks like; Judges ch8 shows what its absence produces.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'judges', c)
    print(f'judges mkt-context: wrote {sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())} verses across ch 7-8')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
